Instead of using macros and out of place `#include` I introduced c++ templates to create easily new coord types.

Cons
- construtor is not a constexpr constructor anymore :-1: 
- lot of code due to limitation on partial template specialization on methods :-1:

Pros
- no wired `#include` and `#defines` :+1:

Actual I am not really convinced anymore if this was the right call to do it with c++ templates. maybe code generation is better :). Or if somebody knows todo this c++ templates better (I wanted to use the  [get&lt;N&gt;](https://github.com/SFTtech/openage/compare/master...spjoe:feature/coord-template?expand=1#diff-19f485c287b0e7d5dede1d170aabae03R17) method on xyz_coord but the compiler did not let me, due to limitations partial template specialization on methods). 

e.g.

``` cpp
template <typename AT, typename RT, typename ST, unsigned int N>
RT absolute_xyz_coord<AT, RT, ST, N>::as_relative() const {
        RT retval;
        for (unsigned int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
                retval.get<i>() = this->get<i>();
        }
        return retval;
}
```

Compiler should be able to do unrolling at compile time (N is known).
